      "id": "4d2f7a0a9edd120014957a1cb42b37f8aff300d0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2012-01-06 21:02:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nFan Yong has pointed out that the conditions under which various operations are tallied are not entirely clear or consistent.  For named system calls the standard behavior in Lustre is to tally them on successful completion.  This makes good \"does what it says on the can\" sense, and should be upheld.\n\nFor other operations (like lookup()) this standard is unsatisfactory, since cached lookup is low cost and not worth recording, while unsuccessful MDT lookup can have a real cost (think of running a python script from a loop at scale).\n\nIn patch 5, I have pulled the controversial lookup and revalidate stats so that the rest might go through.  I will create a new LU+change for them so that we can work on a coherent policy for their use.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
